          "text": "The user wants to verify that the output contains exactly one specific line and nothing else. They have a test case with mixed points - some pass the filter, some don't. They want to check both that the passing point IS in the output AND that nothing else (no extra lines) is in the output.\n\nLet me think about how to check \"exactly one line, and it's the expected one\" in a .bat file.\n\nApproach:\n1. First verify the expected string IS present: `findstr /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\" build\\main_out.txt > nul`\n2. Then verify the file has exactly one line. In cmd, `findstr /R /C:\".\"` matches any non-empty line. We need to count lines.\n\nActually, a simpler approach for \"exactly this one line and nothing else\":\n1. `findstr /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\"` - checks it IS there\n2. Then check the file size is exactly the length of that one line + newline. But that's fragile.\n\nBetter: use `find /C /V \"\"` to count lines in cmd (unlike findstr, `find` counts all lines):\n```\ntype build\\main_out.txt | find /C /V \"\" > build\\line_count.txt\n```\nThen extract the count. But this is clunky.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach in .bat:\n1. Check that expected line exists: `findstr /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\" build\\main_out.txt > nul`\n2. Check that the file ends after that line - by verifying that the expected line **is** the content and there's nothing else:\n   - One way: invert findstr to check NO OTHER lines exist. `findstr /V /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\" build\\main_out.txt > nul` - `/V` outputs lines that DON'T match. If anything is output (errorlevel 0), there are other lines.\n\nWait, `/V` shows lines that do NOT match the pattern. So if there's only one line \"4.000 5.000 5.000\", then `/V` will find no lines (errorlevel 1). If there are extra lines, `/V` will find them (errorlevel 0).\n\nSo the combo:\n```bat\nfindstr /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\" build\\main_out.txt > nul\nif errorlevel 1 echo FAIL: expected line not found & exit /b 1\n\nfindstr /V /C:\"4.000 5.000 5.000\" build\\main_out.txt > nul\nif not errorlevel 1 echo FAIL: extra content found & exit /b 1\n```\n\nThis is elegant because:\n- If the file has the expected line → first findstr succeeds (errorlevel 0 → if errorlevel 1 doesn't trigger → OK)\n- If the file has ONLY that line → second findstr `/V` finds no non-matching lines → errorlevel 1 → `if not errorlevel 1` doesn't trigger → OK\n- If the file has extra content → second findstr `/V` finds them → errorlevel 0 → `if not errorlevel 1` triggers → FAIL\n- If the expected line is missing → first findstr fails → FAIL\n\nThis is exactly what the user needs!",
