          "text": "The user wants to check if a specific multi-line block of text (like a 3x3 matrix) is in the output. They're asking how to use findstr for this, specifically for a case like task 1 where the output is a matrix.\n\nFor task 1 (distance matrix), the output is an N×N matrix of numbers. If they want to verify specific values with findstr, they have a few options:\n\n1. Use findstr with multiple patterns using /C: for each line they want to check\n2. Use multiple separate findstr calls, each checking one specific row value\n3. Use findstr with a regex to match a pattern\n\nBut the key issue is: the matrix output has many numbers per line. Let me think about what approach works for a matrix.\n\nFor example, for N=3, the output might be:\n```\n    0.000    1.732    1.732\n    1.732    0.000    1.732\n    1.732    1.732    0.000\n```\n\nTo verify this with findstr, you could:\n1. Check that specific cells have the right values (e.g., row 1 col 1 is 0.000, row 1 col 2 is 1.732, etc.)\n2. Or check that each row contains the expected pattern\n\nBut actually, findstr searches for a pattern anywhere on a line, not at a specific position. So if you search for \"0.000\" you'll match any line containing 0.000 (which could be all of them if there are zero-distance entries).\n\nLet me think about what the user is specifically asking. They wrote \"условных 2 3 4\\n 1 2 3\\n 5 6 7\" - they're showing a hypothetical matrix output and asking how to verify it with findstr.\n\nWait, they said \"для условных 2 3 4\\n 1 2 3\\n 5 6 7\". I think they mean: if the output of the program is:\n```\n2.000 3.000 4.000\n1.000 2.000 3.000\n5.000 6.000 7.000\n```\n\nHow to check this with findstr? \n\nActually, I think the user is asking about findstr for multi-line output verification in general, not specifically about a matrix. They might be referring to how to check multiple lines of output.\n\nFor task 1 (distance matrix), there are a few approaches:\n\n1. Check specific cells/values: `findstr /C:\"0.000\"` won't work well because all diagonal entries are 0.000.\n\n2. Check that a specific formatted row is present: `findstr /C:\"0.000    1.732    1.732\"` - would work if the spacing matches exactly.\n\n3. Or use multiple findstr calls with `/C:` to check critical values.\n\nLet me think about what the user actually needs. They asked \"как сделать findstr для условных 2 3 4\\n 1 2 3\\n 5 6 7\" - literally \"how to do findstr for conditional 2 3 4 / 1 2 3 / 5 6 7\".\n\nI think they're asking about the approach for task 1: the matrix output has multiple rows and columns, so how to use findstr to verify the output. They might be wondering whether to check every cell, or just a few key ones.\n\nFor task 1, a good approach would be:\n- The matrix is symmetric with zeros on diagonal\n- For N=3, distances are: d(1,2)=d(2,1)=1.732, d(1,3)=d(3,1)=1.732, d(2,3)=d(3,2)=1.732 (because all vertices of an equilateral triangle have the same distance)\n- For N=4 (square), distances are more varied: diagonal=0, adjacent=1.414 (sqrt(2)), opposite=2.000\n- You only need to check a few specific values, not the whole matrix\n\nSo the approach would be:\n1. Check that line 1 contains \"0.000\" (diagonal element) — but this appears on every line, not very useful\n2. Check a specific formatted row: `findstr /C:\"0.000    1.732    1.732\"` for N=3\n3. Or better: use `findstr /R` with regex to check a few key values\n\nActually, I think the most practical approach for the matrix task is:\n- Pick N=4 (square), which gives more varied distances\n- Check that certain specific formatted rows appear in the output\n- Or use `findstr /B` to match beginning of line if the format is tabular enough\n\nBut wait, the user might not be asking about task 1 specifically with this question. Let me re-read: \"как сделать findstr для условных 2 3 4\\n 1 2 3\\n 5 6 7\"\n\nI think they're just giving an example output format and asking generally how to verify multi-line output with findstr. The answer would be:\n\n- Check that certain specific values appear in the output (multiple `findstr /C:` calls)\n- To verify a whole line, match the exact formatted line including spacing\n- For a matrix, you don't need to check every cell — just a few strategically chosen ones\n\nLet me give a clear, practical answer.",
